  "summary": "Section 1.8 covers solving quadratic equations using multiple methods. Factoring uses the zero product property and works when the quadratic factors nicely. The square root method is efficient for equations of the form $x^2 = k$ or $(x + p)^2 = q$. Completing the square transforms any quadratic into vertex form, allowing solution by square roots. The quadratic formula $x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$ works for all quadratic equations. The discriminant $b^2 - 4ac$ determines solution type without solving: positive → two real solutions, zero → one real solution (double root), negative → two complex solutions. Applications include projectile motion, geometry problems, and optimization. Choosing the most efficient method depends on the equation's form - factoring for simple quadratics, square root for squared binomials, completing square for $a = 1$ with even $b$, and quadratic formula for messy coefficients.",

